text:
I think HBox really underestimated Wizzy's patience and ability to zone efficiently.

Wizzy did both of those things incredibly well, especially on Dreamland. Actually, counter-picking to Dreamland was probably a mistake, since Wizzy has always been good on that stage (in every Smash game).

If anything HBox should have noticed the heavy use of platform zoning (especially by using variations of movement via Falcon's speed) and adjusted by counter-picking to another stage (Fountain of Dreams perhaps).

text: It is just so crazy how easily a lot of her fans dropped her after electra heart. But the fans who stayed and grew into 'Froot' REALLY understood her strategy and what she was trying to get across. 'Electra Heart' was such a theatrical and almost superficial album and i think a lot of diamonds understood that this was just an era; That her upcoming music wasn't going to turn into something that sounded like 'Electra Heart.' And Froot was a way of establishing herself as an artist thus creating her immense satisfactory in the era. She finally got her art across in the way that she had always dreamed. And I think that is why I respect her so much. Because she has worked so hard to develop and recreate her art and it happened. It finally and gradually happened and I feel a sense of this "Marina & The Diamonds" trilogy coming to an end. Because NOW she has defined herself as an artist and this upcoming music whenever it arrives is going to be experimental and challenging. I think this next era is going to be VERY different.

text:
This video was especially interesting for me having completed a personal project, merging the map and scenario of Diplomacy with the rules mechanics of A Game of Thrones (the board game). In coming up with all the leader cards, I probably did more research than I ever would have thought of doing in school. Nothing to do with this video but just commenting on the timing of its release.
Britain's motive in the war was not hard to understand. Britain has always valued its independence from the mainland of Europe. Through its history, its foreign policy was mostly concerned with the balance of power in mainland Europe. While Germany was a disunited collection of principalities, Britain often fought with them against France. When the balance shifted with Germany's unification, it made sense to switch sides and make up with France. The last thing Britain would want to see is Europe unified under any one power. The two times in history they were most threatened is when one empire gained dominance, even if temporarily (first Napoleon and then Hitler).¬†
